### Feature Engineering and Categorical Summaries 

Grouping job titles streamlines analysis, enhances visualization clarity, and enables models to learn from meaningful categories rather than 1,000+ unique values. Because title is a key component of our analysis, it is essential to structure this variable in a way that maximizes its analytical usefulness and predictive value.  

It is important to note that first match will win.  I.e. because Manager is listed above engineering in the code if some one were to enter "Engineering Manager"  it will be categorized as Manager.  

```{r Contact Lead Title }

#feature engineering to make meaningful subgroups for contact lead title that was an open text field and resulted in 6589 different title results.  This buckets the 6589 into 6.   

Data3 <- Data2 %>% mutate(contact.lead.title = case_when( grepl("Manager|Director|Head|Executive|President", contact.lead.title, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Management", grepl("Engineer|Developer|Programmer|Scientist|Chemist|Inspector|Technologist|Quality", contact.lead.title, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Engineering", grepl("Sales|Account|Business", contact.lead.title, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Sales", grepl("Analyst|Consultant", contact.lead.title, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Analytics", grepl("Marketing|Communications", contact.lead.title, ignore.case = TRUE) ~ "Marketing", TRUE ~ "Other" ))
```


This loop is designed to summarize all categorical variables in relation to the target variable. It helps us understand how each category is distributed within the target, revealing which categories have higher or lower conversion rates. Additionally, this loop aids in feature engineering (e.g., grouping titles) and informs modeling decisions by highlighting variables with strong predictive power.


```{r Loop for conversions }

#factoring variables 
cat_vars <- names(Data3)[sapply(Data3, function(x) is.character(x) | is.factor(x))]

#removing unwanted variables 
cat_vars <- setdiff(cat_vars, 
                    c("QAL.ID", 
                      "qal.cohort.date", 
                      "contact.lead.id",
                      "next_stage__c"))


#loop for each variable to group by variable and report on conversion rate 
for (var in cat_vars) {
  
  cat("====", var, "====\n")
  
  summary_table <- Data3 %>%
    group_by(.data[[var]]) %>%
    summarise(
      Count = n(),
      ConversionRate = round(mean(Target), 3),
      .groups = "drop"
    ) %>%
    arrange(desc(ConversionRate))
  
  print(head(summary_table, 8))
  cat("\n\n")
}
```


Several patterns emerge from the categorical summaries:

**Industry**: Blood & Biologics and Medical Device segments show higher conversion rates relative to Non-Life Science. This will be something to explore later.  

**Title**: Management and Engineering roles demonstrate stronger conversion performance than Marketing or Other. From experience this makes sense because management and engineering roles are the decision makers in most companies.  They identify the need and find the solution.  They will be the ones to identify if Master Control products will suffice the needs of their company.  

**Territory**: Leads in the Americas demonstrate higher conversion rates compared to APAC & Oceania and EMEA. This aligns with expectations, as MasterControl’s quality management solutions are particularly relevant in highly regulated markets, many of which are concentrated in the Americas. However, this finding warrants further investigation. During preliminary data review, we identified potential character encoding issues affecting non-English entries. It is possible that data quality inconsistencies may have contributed to lower observed performance in APAC, and this should be validated before drawing firm conclusions.

**Company Tier**: Smaller and medium accounts convert at higher rates than large enterprises. We believe this is because large enterprises handle their QMS and manufacturing ERP systems internally with dedicated resources. Smaller accounts likely have higher conversions because they need the support of trained professional and a plug and play system.  

**Campaign Channel**: Direct/Inbound and SEO generate substantially higher conversion rates than outbound prospecting. This is most generally the case for any conversion.  Someone actively seeking a tool to assist them is going to have a higher conversion than outbound prospecting.  

**Solution Rollup**: Summaries confirm what was provided in Master Controls data write up already stating that Qx (19.5%) significantly outperforms Mx (12.2%), confirming the original business problem. This is the problem we will be addressing through our modeling to improve Mx conversion rates.  


