## EDA Takeaways 

### Visualization Summaries 

When isolating Mx leads, conversion disparities become more pronounced across industry and role segments. Blood & Biologics and Medical Device industries continue to outperform others, suggesting potential ICP refinement opportunities. Additionally, Management and Engineering roles maintain higher conversion rates, reinforcing their influence in manufacturing software purchasing decisions. Manufacturing models also play a key role, with organizations directly involved in production showing significantly higher conversion rates. Geographic variation indicates that industry performance is not uniform across territories, suggesting interaction effects may be important in predictive modeling.

### EDA Key Findings 

Mx conversion (12.2%) significantly under performs Qx (19.5%).

Regulated industries (Blood & Biologics, Medical Device) show strongest Mx conversion.

Management and Engineering roles convert highest.

Small and medium firms outperform large enterprises.

Direct/Inbound and SEO channels yield highest progression.

Industry × Territory interaction likely important for modeling.

## Modeling 

### Implications for Modeling 

The exploratory analysis has identified several high-impact variables that will serve as the foundation for the Mx lead scoring modeling.  The following factors will be central to the feature selection process.  

1. Prioritizing Industry Segementation 

The performance of Blood & Biologics and Medical Device industries confirms that regulatory requirements are a primary driver for Mx adoption.  These should be weighted features 

2. Weighted Scoring for Key Influencers 

The high conversion rates for Management and Engineering roles indicate these are decision makers with influence on purchasing decisions.  Leads with these titles should receive a higher baseline probability in the predictive modeling, helping the sales team to identify the correct entry point within a potential client company.   

3. Capture Multi-Dimensional Interactions 

Our EDA suggests that Industry and Territory interactions also have influence on the conversion rate.  Through logistic regression or tree based models we can explore these interactions to capture non-linear relationships.  

### Modeling Plan 

Our baseline model will start with a logistics regression analysis.  This model is highly interpretable and can directly output a conversion probability between 0 and 1.  With this model we will be able to examine lift from various variable factors, confirming our assumptions with industry and title.  

The second model of choice will be a random forest model because of its ability to handle non-linear relationships.  It can help capture complex patterns in the data to help uncover hidden insights.  


Because we have a binary target we are looking to maximize recall for high-quality leads, maintain reasonable precision, produce lift charts so that Master Control sales team can have success in MX conversions.  

### Feature engineering Primary Site Function 

```{r Feature engineer primary site function }

#Feature engineer the primary site function to limit it into understandable categories  

Data_clean_Mx_modeling <- Mx_data %>%
 mutate(site_group = case_when(
  str_detect(acct.primary.site.function,"injectable|API|biologic|OSD") ~ "Pharma Manufacturing",
  str_detect(acct.primary.site.function,"device|IVD|surgical") ~ "Device Manufacturing",
  str_detect(acct.primary.site.function,"Non-manufacturing") ~ "Non-Manufacturing",
  TRUE ~ "Other Manufacturing"
 ))

```

We created the site_group variable to combine detailed site function descriptions into broader, more meaningful manufacturing categories. This reduces complexity in the data and ensures similar site functions are analyzed together. Grouping these values also makes the dataset easier to use for modeling and improves interpretability of the results.


### Log Model 

```{r Log Model Data 3 }

#model preparation 
set.seed(123)

train_index <- createDataPartition(Data3$Target, p = .7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- Data3[train_index, ]
test_data  <- Data3[-train_index, ]

#log model with weights to try and improve model with target imbalance. 

log_model <- glm(Target ~ acct.target.industry +
                   acct.territory.rollup +
                   acct.tier.rollup +
                   contact.lead.title +
                   last.tactic.campaign.channel +
                   acct.manufacturing.model + 
                   Priority,
                 data = train_data,
                 family = "binomial",
                 weights = ifelse(train_data$Target == 1,3,1))

# keeps log model output clean 
tidy(log_model) %>%
  filter(p.value < 0.05) %>%
  mutate(odds_ratio = exp(estimate)) %>%
  arrange(desc(abs(estimate)))

# this would show the complete output for the log model 
#summary(log_model)

```

```{r log model data 3 pred}

#pulls in log model, provides a pred value if >.5 will identify it as converting.
pred_probs <- predict(log_model, test_data, type = "response")

pred_class <- ifelse(pred_probs > .5, 1, 0)

#confusion matrix to get accuracy, sensitivity, etc for model analysis 
confusionMatrix(as.factor(pred_class), as.factor(test_data$Target))
```


```{r AUC log model data 3}
#produces area under the curve graphic to score model performance

install.packages("pROC")
library(pROC)


roc_obj <- roc(test_data$Target, pred_probs)


auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
print(auc_value)

plot(roc_obj, col = "#1c61b6", lwd = 3, main = "ROC Curve for Logistic Regression Model")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2, col = "gray")  # diagonal line for reference


auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
legend("bottomright", legend = paste("AUC =", round(auc_value, 3)), col = "#1c61b6", lwd = 3)
```

### Log Model Overall Summary 

The logistic regression model was used as the baseline model to predict lead conversion because it is highly interpretable and produces probabilities between 0 and 1. The model showed solid performance with 79% accuracy and an AUC of 0.822, indicating good ability to distinguish between converting and non-converting leads. Results show that medium and small tier accounts, management-level contacts, and high-intent actions such as “Contact Us,” “Live Demo,” and “Website Pricing” significantly increase the likelihood of conversion. In contrast, leads from Non-Life Science industries and several marketing channels such as email, events, and external demand generation showed lower conversion likelihood. Overall, the logistic model helped identify which variables influence conversion, providing interpretable insights that will guide further analysis with Random Forest to capture complex patterns and rank feature importance.

### Random Forest Overall Model 

We decided to implement a Random Forest Model to our analysis to try to discover non-linear relationships in the data.  We have chosen to build 500 trees to learn from and aggregate our predictions to try to improve prediction accuracy.  Does industry and location truly have impacts on each other for conversion? Lastly, we are trying to determine which features are most important to model on.  Is there one feature over another that will have a stronger influence on conversion?  


```{r Random Forest data 3 }
#data preparation 

set.seed(123)

train_index <- createDataPartition(Data3$Target, p = .7, list = FALSE)
train_data <- Data3[train_index, ]
test_data  <- Data3[-train_index, ]

train_data$Target <- as.factor(train_data$Target)
test_data$Target  <- as.factor(test_data$Target)

#random forest model 
rf_model <- randomForest(
  Target ~ acct.target.industry +
           acct.tier.rollup +
           acct.territory.rollup +
           contact.lead.title +
           last.tactic.campaign.channel +
           Priority,
  data = train_data,
  ntree = 500,
  importance = TRUE
)
```


```{r Random Forest pred and AUC}

#generating predictions to test model performance 
print(rf_model)

rf_pred_class <- predict(rf_model, test_data)


rf_pred_prob <- predict(rf_model, test_data, type = "prob")[,2]


#confusion matrix to test sensitivity, accuracy, etc.  
confusionMatrix(rf_pred_class, test_data$Target)

#area under the curve graphic to score model performance 
roc_rf <- roc(as.numeric(test_data$Target), rf_pred_prob)
auc_rf <- auc(roc_rf)
print(auc_rf)

plot(roc_rf,
     col = "darkgreen",
     lwd = 3,
     main = "ROC Curve for Random Forest Model")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2, col = "gray")

legend("bottomright",
       legend = paste("AUC =", round(auc_rf,3)),
       col = "darkgreen",
       lwd = 3)

# Feature Importance
varImpPlot(rf_model)
```


### Random Forest Summary 

A Random Forest classification model was built using 500 trees and included predictors: industry, account tier, territory, lead title, campaign channel, and priority. The model achieved an accuracy of 83.1% with an AUC of 0.778, indicating good but slightly lower predictive performance than our logistic regression model. Again, the results showed the model to be effective at identifying non-converting leads but still struggled with identifying converting leads due to class imbalance.  Feature importance analysis highlighted which variables contribute most to prediction, helping uncover nonlinear relationships and interaction effects in the data.


